{"title_page": "William Lewis (journalist)", "text_new": "{{other people|William Lewis}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = William Lewis\n| image         = \n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1969|04|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| education     = [[Whitefield School]]\n| alma_mater    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of Bristol]]\n* [[Department of Journalism, City University]]\n}}\n| occupation    = CEO of [[Dow Jones and Company]]\n| boards        = [[Associated Press]]<ref>https://www.ap.org/about/our-people/leadership-team\n</ref>\n| years_active  = \n| employer      = [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]]\n| known_for     = Publishing the story which led to the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]]; Role as executive member of News Corp's Management and Standards Committee following the [[News International phone hacking scandal]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage| Rebecca Slater |1995}}\n| notable_works = \n| children      = 4\n| relatives     = [[Simon Lewis (public relations officer)|Simon Lewis]] (brother)\n}}\n'''William Lewis''' (born 2 April 1969)<ref name=\"Observer2009\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/24/will-lewis-daily-telegraph-profile|title =Will Lewis: the man with an expense account\n|last=Anthony|first=Andrew|date=May 24, 2009|website=Guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> is a British media executive and was formerly chief executive of [[Dow Jones and Company]] and publisher of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''. Earlier in his career he was known as a journalist and then editor.\n\nWhile Editor of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name= \"GuardianMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/18/mps-expenses-how-scoop-came-light |title = MPs' expenses: how scoop came to light \u2013 and why journalists fear a 'knock on the door'|last=Brook|first=Stephen|date=May 18, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis led the team that broke the story of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|MPs' expenses scandal]],  which led to the resignation of the [[Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[Michael Martin, Baron Martin of Springburn|Michael Martin]], a further six government ministers and the creation of [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]].<ref>http://www.theipsa.org.uk</ref>\n\nFrom September 2010<ref name= \"MarketingweekNI\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/news-international-hires-will-lewis-to-fill-new-role/ |title = News International hires Will Lewis to fill new role\n|last=Fernandez|first=Joe|date=July 8, 2010|website=Marketingweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> to July 2011, Lewis worked as General Manager of the newspaper publisher [[News International]], playing a role in the company's response to the phone hacking crisis.  In July 2011, following the closure of the ''[[News of the World]]'', Lewis left News International to join the Management and Standards Committee, an independent division led by [[Anthony Grabiner, Baron Grabiner|Lord Grabiner QC]], created by the News Corp board to orchestrate cooperation with multiple law enforcement investigations into News International.\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nWilliam Lewis was born and raised in Hampstead Garden Suburb, North London, England. His father David Lewis M.B.E,<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/news/queens-birthday-honours-2010</ref> worked as a Managing Director of a packaging company and his mother Sally was a teacher. Lewis's primary education was at Brookland Junior school in Hampstead Garden Suburb. His secondary education was at Whitefield school, a comprehensive school in the London Borough of Barnet. After achieving his A levels, Lewis studied for a BSc in Politics and Economics at [[University of Bristol|Bristol University]], where he wrote for the student newspaper, ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]'',<ref name=\"Observer2009\"/> and captained the University 1st football team. Following university Lewis completed a postgraduate diploma in Periodical Journalism at [[City University London|City University]].\n\nIn 1991, Lewis was hired as a finance reporter by ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''.<ref name= \"LevesonLewis\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.discoverleveson.com/witness/Will_Lewis/3960/?bc=1#witnessevidence|title =Witness Statement of William Lewis\n|last=Lewis|first=William|date=January 10, 2012|website=Discoverleveson.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> In 1994 he left the tabloid to take a job in the ''[[Financial Times]]''{{'}} investigative unit. He later became fund management correspondent and then mergers and acquisitions correspondent.<ref name= \"LevesonLewis\"/> In 1999, while posted at the New York office he broke the story of the [[ExxonMobil]] merger,<ref name= \"DowJonesBio\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.dowjones.com/team/william-lewis-3/\n|title =Official biography\n|website=DowJones.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> the biggest industrial merger in US corporate history. The scoop surprised the US business media and helped establish the ''Financial Times'' in the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archives.cjr.org/cover_story/a_narrowed_gaze.php|title=A Narrowed Gaze|last=Starkman|first=Dean|date=January 2012|website=Columbia Journalism Review|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Following this Lewis was promoted to Global News Editor.<ref name=\"Marketing Week2006\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/daily-telegraph-appoints-william-lewis-editor/\n|title =Daily Telegraph appoints William Lewis editor\n|last=Week|first=Marketing|date=Oct 9, 2006|website=marketingweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> He was then poached to become Business Editor at ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', where he remained for three years, from 2002 to 2005.\n\n==Telegraph Media Group==\n\nLewis joined the [[Telegraph Media Group]] as city editor in August 2005 and was made deputy editor of ''The Telegraph'' while he was still working out his notice from ''The Sunday Times''. In October 2006 he became ''The Daily Telegraph''{{'s}} youngest ever editor.<ref name= \"Independent2006\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/will-lewis-the-daily-telegraphs-youngest-ever-editor-426919.html\n|title =Will Lewis: TheDaily Telegraph's youngest ever editor\n|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=Dec 4, 2006|website=Independent.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nOn joining ''The Telegraph'', Lewis described the newspaper as a \"shambles\", with \"no innovation, no culture of improvement, no understanding of the need to perform, of needing to work with your colleagues rather than be at war with them.\"<ref name= \"MediaGuardian100\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jul/11/will-lewis-mediaguardian-100-2009\n|title =The MPs' expenses triumph makes Will Lewis of the Telegraph the highest-rising newspaper editor in the MediaGuardian 100\n|date=July 13, 2009|website=Guardian.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs editor he took control of the newspaper during period of tumultuous change thanks to the decline in print sales and display advertising revenue.<ref name= \"GuardianSweney2009\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jul/13/telegraph-media-group-2008-results|title = Telegraph Media Group reports \u00a315.7m pre-tax loss for 2008|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=July 13, 2009|website=Guardian.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nLewis designed the layout of ''The Telegraph''{{'s}} new Victoria newsroom<ref name= \"MarketingWeekNov2006\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/right-message-wrong-reader/|title = Right Message, Wrong Reader|last=Week|first=Marketing|date=Nov 2, 2006|website=MarketingWeek.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> and saw through the modernisation program which involved senior staff cuts. The move was initially felt to be in conflict with the newspaper's brand and aging readership.<ref name= \"MarketingWeekNov2006\"/>\n\nIn 2007 he was made editor-in-chief of TMG.<ref name= \"DowJonesBio\"/>\n\nDuring his time as editor, he also attempted a broader debate at ''The Telegraph'' about the environment. While the newspapers and website continued to house [[global warming deniers]] such as [[Christopher Booker]] and [[James Delingpole]],<ref>James Randerson [https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2009/feb/25/climate-change-denial-christopher-booker \"Christopher Booker's wilful climate change ignorance gathers pace\"], ''The Guardian'', 25 February 2009</ref> he also recruited Geoffrey Lean, the environmental commentator to write a weekly column and lead the ''Telegraph'''s global warming coverage.<ref>Mark Sweney [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/08/geoffrrey-lean-independent-sunday \"Environment editor Geoffrey Lean to leave Independent on Sunday\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 June 2009</ref>\n\n==Role in the Parliamentary Expenses Scandal==\n\nLewis's involvement in the scandal began when he was told by colleagues that they had been approached by an intermediary on behalf of a source who said that they had four years' worth of MPs' data copied onto a disk. After establishing that the paper would not be breaking the law by accepting the disc, and that the story was in the public interest, Lewis approved negotiation with the intermediary.<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\">{{Cite web|url=https://leveson.sayit.mysociety.org/hearing-10-january-2012/mr-william-lewis|title =Leveson Inquiry, Hearing of Mr William Lewis\n|last=Lewis|first=William|date=January 10, 2012|website=leveson.sayit.mysociety.org|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Lewis told [[the Leveson Inquiry]]: \"the reason [the source] had come to the Telegraph was he wanted to ensure fair and balanced coverage. He wanted to be certain that the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MPs and the Conservative MPs all had their chance to have their day in the sun, as it were.\"<ref name= \"Journalism.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.journalism.co.uk/news/telegraph-paid-middleman--150-000-for-expenses-data/s2/a547418/|title = Telegraph paid middleman \u00a3150,000 for expenses data\n|last=Gunter|first=Joel|date=January 10, 2012|website=Journalism.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> The intermediary, a former [[Special Air Service|SAS]] officer John Wick,<ref name= \"GuardianMPsExpenses\"/> had already offered the story to a number of other newspapers, all of whom had been reluctant to take the risk of publishing, or meet the price set by Wick.<ref name= \"GuardianMPsExpenses\"/>\n\nOnce Lewis's team concluded negotiations with the source,  the Telegraph team had only ten days to investigate the data on the disk which meant wading through more than a million documents.<ref name= \"KirkupMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5563129/MPs-expenses-Out-today-the-censored-version-of-every-MPs-expense-claims.html|title = MPs' expenses: censored version MPs' expenses claims goes online|last=Kirkup|first=James|date=May 18, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Once Lewis saw the information on the disc he realised that he had to run the story. Lewis told [[Brian Leveson|Lord Leveson]]:  \"I became very aware that it was my responsibility to bring this to the public domain. It was no longer going to be a choice for me as editor.\"<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\"/><ref name= \"BBCMPsExpenses\" >{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16494872|title = Leveson Inquiry: Telegraph expenses scoop explained|last=News|first=BBC|date= Jan 10, 2012|website=bbc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLewis stressed to his colleagues that he wanted the Telegraph to be seen as be fair and balanced in their approach. They concluded that they should start with the government and then move into the opposition as it was then, [[the Conservative Party (UK)|the Conservative Party]].<ref name= \"Journalism.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe next stage involved the team writing to each MP to put them on notice that a story was being written, and then to wait for the replies. The first MP to revert to the Telegraph team was [[Secretary of State for Justice]] [[Jack Straw]].<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\"/> Straw replied, confirming the information in the letter and explaining his expenses. Lewis told the Leveson enquiry: \"Only then did I feel able to give the green light to publication that evening.\" He added, \"I remain hugely proud of -- given the intensity with which the MPs' expenses team had to work, the incredible pressure they worked under, continual threat of trying to be stopped what they were doing, I think this record is one we should be proud of.\"<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\"/> He added: \"I was also aware that this story was laced with risk all round, as the best and most important journalism tends to be.''<ref name= \"BBCMPsExpenses\"/>\n\n===Aftermath of Parliamentary Expenses Scandal===\n\nThe publication of the story led to the resignation of the Speaker of the House of Commons, [[Michael Martin, Baron Martin of Springburn|Michael Martin]], a further six government ministers and the creation of the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority.<ref name= \"BBCAftermathMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48187096|title = MPs' expenses: The Legacy of a Scandal|last=Flinders|first=Professor Matthew|date=May 7, 2019|website=bbc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  A police investigation into the leak was called off in May 2009. A statement issued by Scotland Yard said that although the unauthorised disclosure of information appeared to \"breach public duty\", much of the information was in the process of being prepared for release under the Freedom of Information Act.<ref name= \"PoliceInvestigationMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/may/19/expenses-leak-police|title = MPs' expenses: police will not investigate leaks to media|last=Mulholland|first=Helene|date=May 19, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lewis spoke publicly for the first time about the scandal in a [[BBC Radio 4]] Interview with the BBC Political Editor [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]].<ref name= \"NickRobinsonGuardianMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/30/will-lewis-daily-telegraph-mps-expenses|title = Telegraph's Will Lewis: MPs lost moral authority long before expenses scandal|last=Luft|first=Oliver|date=June 30, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  In the interview Lewis responded to claims by that his newspaper's coverage had irreparably damaged parliament and democracy as  \"Absolute, complete rubbish.\" In the interview Lewis claimed: \"It is going to open up parliament to a whole new generation of people who understand what it means to be a representative of British citizens,\" he said. He described the removal of criminal MPs from Parliament as \"undeniably a good thing for the United Kingdom.\"\n\nIn a 2017 in an interview with the ''[[Evening Standard]]'',<ref name= \"ESlordofwallstreet\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/business/will-lewis-the-brit-lord-of-wall-street-on-his-battle-with-social-media-giants-and-fake-news-a3625046.html|title = TWill Lewis: The Brit lord of Wall Street on his battle with social media giants and fake news|last=Gwyther|first=Matthew|date=September 1, 2017|website=standard.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis said: \"I think MPs' expenses began that disgust with the political class. Brexit has to be seen within that context. If the House of Lords is our main defence against stupidity, that doesn't make me very happy.\"\n\nIn 2019, Lewis appeared on [[BBC]] documentary marking the 10th anniversary of the scandal.<ref name= \"BBCLewisQueen\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-47669586|title = MPs' expenses editor 'more resolute' after Queen talk|last=News|first=BBC|date=March 25, 2019|website=standard.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis talked about establishment hostility towards the Telegraph newsroom and mentioned a brief meeting with [[Elizabeth II|HM Queen]] wherein she indicated her support and sympathy for the story. Lewis has never disclosed the details of the conversation.\n\nIn a 2019 ''[[New Statesmen]]'' article<ref name= \"NewStatesman\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/05/mps-expenses-very-british-scandal|title = MPs' expenses: a very British scandal|last=Lewis|first=William|date=May 1, 2019|website=standard.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis wrote that the scandal was a missed opportunity:  \"The chance to make radical reforms to our political institutions and how they operate was, however, glaringly (and deliberately) overlooked\u2026. Perhaps the fallout from [[Brexit]] will trigger the root-and-branch reform we need before these challenges can ever hope to be met with the sort of honesty, energy and imagination they demand. Optimistic, perhaps, but real change could be achieved if politicians from across the spectrum \u2013 or people from around Britain who have not previously been involved in politics \u2013 begin to share a proper understanding of where the national interest lies and where it will lie in the very near future.\"\n\n==Departure from the Telegraph Group==\n\nIn the summer of 2009, Lewis took a two-month sabbatical from TMG to attend the [[Advanced Management Program]] at [[Harvard Business School]] \u2013 a compressed version of the college's famed Masters in Business Administration. Towards the end of this period Lewis was joined by TMG chief executive [[Murdoch MacLennan]] who stayed to hammer out Lewis's future at TMG.<ref name= \"ESlordofwallstreet\"/><ref name= \"GuardianHarvard\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2010/jul/09/will-lewis-harvard-business-school|title = Will Lewis and the Harvard Business School big guns|last=Monkey|first=Media|date=July 9, 2010|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Lewis returned to the UK, and founded Euston Partners, a digital development division based in Euston, London, staffed by a team of Telegraph employees.<ref name= \"CampaignNov2009\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/lewis-head-digital-telegraph-group/969846|title = Lewis to head digital for Telegraph group|last=Bowser|first=Jackie|date=November 26, 2009|website=campaign.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  The aim of the division was to find a way for newspapers to make money from the emerging App economy.<ref name= \"PressGazetteEuston\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/euston-partners-dispute-may-have-prompted-lewis-exit/|title = Euston Partners dispute may have prompted Lewis exit|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date= May 6, 2010|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  In January 2010 Lewis took the title of Managing Director Digital, while retaining his position of group editor in chief.  Shortly after this he gave up the daily running of ''Sunday'' and ''Daily Telegraph''. He was succeeded in the editor's chair by [[Tony Gallagher]] in late 2009, but remained editor-in-chief.<ref name= \"PressGazetteMDDigital\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/new-telegraph-editor-as-will-lewis-becomes-md-digital/|title = New Telegraph editor as Will Lewis becomes MD digital|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date= Nov 26, 2009|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2010 British Press Awards, ''The Telegraph'' was named the \"National Newspaper of the Year\" for its coverage of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|MPs' expenses scandal]] (named \"Scoop of the Year\"), with Lewis winning \"Journalist of the Year\" for his role.<ref name= \"PressGazetteAward\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/british-press-awards-2010-full-list-of-winners/|title = British Press Awards 2010: Full list of winners|last=Gazette|first=Press|date= Nov 26, 2009|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=March 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccepting his award Lewis said: \"If there was ever a story that proved that news still sells newspapers I suspect this was it.\"<ref name= \"GuardianPressAwards\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/mar/24/british-press-awards-2010-telegraph-expenses|title = Daily Telegraph dominates British Press Awards with expenses expos\u00e9|last=Brook|first=Stephen|date=March 24, 2010|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite this success, all was not well within TMG. Lewis wanted to create a standalone business with a \"start-up mentality\" from the digital unit, whereas MacLennan wanted the Euston-based project to remain within his control at TMG.<ref name= \"MarketingWeekQuits\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/will-lewis-quits-telegraph-media-group/|title = Will Lewis Quits Telegraph Media Group|last=McEleny|first=Charlottle|date= May 6, 2010|website=marketingweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2010}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianTelegraphExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/10/will-lewis-telegraph-digital-strategy|title = Will Lewis's exit puts big question over Telegraph's digital strategy|last=Martinson|first=Jane|date=May 10, 2010|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  Unable to come to an agreement with MacLennan, Lewis departed on May 5, 2010,<ref name= \"FTTelegraphExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.ft.com/content/6b7a97ac-588d-11df-9921-00144feab49a|title = Lewis departs from Telegraph Group|last=Fenton|first=Ben|date=May 5, 2010|website=ft.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> just six months. The split was described in the press as \"amicable\" but that Maclennan had been \"impatient to see results\". TMG said they would continue to maintain the digital division.<ref name= \"PressGazetteLewisExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/abrupt-exit-for-will-lewis-after-five-years-at-telegraph/|title = Abrupt exit for Will Lewis after five years at Telegraph|last=Gazette|first=Press|date= May 6, 2010|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=March 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==News International==\n\nIn September 2010 Lewis was hired by News International as group general manager. A key part of this new role was to modernise the company and create streamlined digital newsrooms as he had done at TMG.<ref name= \"GuardianRhids\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/24/will-lewis-telegraph-news-international |title = Will Lewis hires his old Telegraph lieutenants for News International roles\n|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=July 8, 2010|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianMSCExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/20/phone-hacking-will-lewis-news-corp |title = Will Lewis likely to leave as News Corp rejigs phone-hacking clean-up team\n|last=Sabbagh|first=Dan|date=July 20, 2012|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlmost immediately on joining, an article in ''[[The New York Times]]'' caused the ongoing issue of illegal phone message interception by the ''News of the World'' to flare up.<ref name= \"NYTphonehacking\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/05/magazine/05hacking-t.html |title = Tabloid Hack Attack on Royals, and Beyond\n|last=Van Natta Jr|first=Don|date=September 1, 2010|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nTowards the end of 2010, Lewis was informed that the company was facing a large number of civil actions relating to phone hacking.<ref name= \"GuardianPCC\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/21/phone-hacking-news-of-the-world|title = PCC to re-examine News of the World phone-hacking evidence\n|last=Robinson|first=James|date=September 21, 2010|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nOn 10 January, Lewis sent out a formal instruction to the IT staff at News International that all evidence relevant to various civil and criminal actions was to be retained on News International's email servers.<ref name= \"HackAttack\">{{cite book |last=Davis |first=Nick |date= |title=Hack Attack: How the truth caught up with Rupert Murdoch |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LVjyAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA324&lpg=PA324&dq=Will+lewis+evidence+preservation+news+international&source=bl&ots=nHz5lK8JB4&sig=ACfU3U10Qakbb2X_fVeqf8IhTjjGC1PkdQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjHoPyR0KnnAhVeTxUIHdQrDiQQ6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Will%20lewis%20evidence%20preservation%20news%20international&f=false |location= |publisher=Random House |page=324 |isbn=9780099572367 |author-link=}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianBrooksMore\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/nov/27/rebekah-brooks-news-international-emails|title = Rebekah Brooks 'ordered deletion of millions of News International emails'\n|last=Davies|first=Nick|date=November 27, 2013|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLewis remained as general manager as the crisis grew. In the aftermath of revelations by ''The Guardian'' that ''News Of the World'' reporters had deleted voicemails of the murdered school girl, [[Murder of Milly Dowler|Milly Dowler]], the ''News of the World'' was closed.<ref name= \"GuardianBrooks\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/mar/03/rebekah-brooks-shutting-news-of-world-protect-bskyb-bid|title = Rebekah Brooks discussed shutting NoW to protect BSkyB bid\n|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=March 3, 2014|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe stepped down as group general manager in July 2011 to take a role as an executive member of the Management and Standards Committee, an independent division of News Corp mandated by the board to cooperate fully with all authorities investigating wrongdoing at News International.<ref name= \"PRWeekMSC\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.prweek.com/article/1080633/news-internationals-will-lewis-simon-greenberg-seconded-newscorp|title = News International's Will Lewis and Simon Greenberg seconded to NewsCorp\n|last=Rogers|first=Danny|date=July 18, 2011|website=prweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Management and Standards Committee==\n\nThe formal establishment of the Management and Standards Committee was confirmed on July 18, 2011. The MSC was chaired by [[Anthony Grabiner, Baron Grabiner|Lord Grabiner QC]], a senior commercial lawyer, taking legal advice from the law firm [[Linklaters]]. The MSC reported directly to News Corp board members [[Joel Klein]] and [[Viet D. Dinh|Viet Dinh]].  Both Dinh and Klein were former US Assistant Attorney Generals. Lewis, was named in the press release as a \"full time executive member.<ref name= \"NewsCorpMSCannouce\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://newscorp.com/corporate-governance/uk-newspaper-matters/management-and-standards-committee/|title = Management and Standards Committee\n|last=Corp|first=News|date=2013|website=newscorp.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianNewsCorpMSCannouce\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jul/18/news-corp-hacking-scandal/|title = News Corp appoints independent chairman to deal with hacking scandal|last=Deans|first=Jason|date=July 18, 2011|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Terms of Reference were published on 21 July 2011.<ref name= \"NewsUKMSCterms\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.news.co.uk/2011/07/news-corporations-management-and-standards-committee-msc-has-today-thursday-july-21-published-its-terms-of-reference-tor/|title = News Corporation's Management and Standards Committee (MSC) has today (Thursday, July 21) published its Terms of Reference (ToR)\n|last=Corp|first=News|date=July 21, 2011|website=news.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  \"The MSC was authorised to cooperate fully with all relevant investigations and inquiries in the News of the World phone hacking case, police payments and all other related issues across News International, as well as conducting its own enquiries where appropriate.\"\n\nThe MSC included 100 legal staff from Linklaters, as well as forensic advisers from [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]]. Their role was to review all law enforcement requests for evidence and comply if those requests were relevant to the various ongoing investigations.<ref name= \"ReutersInsideMSC\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-newsinternational/insight-inside-rupert-murdochs-uk-newspaper-clean-up-operation-idUSTRE8110PE20120202|title = Insight: Inside Rupert Murdoch's UK newspaper clean-up operation\n|last=Prodhan|first=Georgina|date=February 2, 2012|website=reuters.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Metropolitan Police Service]] investigations [[Operation Weeting]] (phone hacking) and [[Operation Elveden]] (corruption of public officials) resulted in a string of arrests of News International journalists from October 2011 to Mid 2012, prompting complaints from Sun staff that the paper was subject to a \"witch hunt.\"<ref name= \"NewsCorpCivilWar\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/9080015/News-Corp-descends-into-civil-war-after-latest-Sun-arrests.html|title = News Corp descends into civil war after latest Sun arrests\n|last=Ward|first=Victoria|date=February 13, 2012|website=telegraph.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  Though no Sun journalists were successfully convicted by Operation Elveden, ''News of the World'' feature writer Dan Evans received a 10-month suspended sentence. Operation Weeting successfully convicted ''News of the World'' journalists Neville Thurlbeck and [[Greg Miskiw]] who were both sentenced to six months in prison. Former ''News of the World'' editor [[Andy Coulson]] received an 18-month sentence.<ref name= \"BBCElvedenlegacy\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-35666520|title = Operation Elveden corruption probe ends\n|last=News|first=BBC|date=February 26, 2016|website=bbc.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"BBCWeetingConvictions\">{{Cite web|url= \n https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-28160626|title = Andy Coulson jailed for 18 months over phone hacking\n|last=News|first=BBC|date=July 4, 2014|website=bbc.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 20 July 2012, Lewis began the process of departing the MSC.<ref name= \"GuardianMSCExit\"/>\n\n===Vince Cable leak allegation===\n\nIn December 2010, ''Daily Telegraph'' reporters secretly recorded the UK Business Secretary [[Vince Cable]] making a number of unguarded remarks about the UK government and also his view that \"we have declared war on [[Rupert Murdoch|Murdoch]]\". ''The Telegraph'' reported the remarks about government, but did not publish his views on Murdoch. These views were controversial, because Cable was overseeing in a sub-judicial role the bid by Murdoch's [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] for all of [[BSkyB]]. The remarks about Murdoch were leaked to the BBC's Business Editor, [[Robert Peston]].<ref name=reuters1>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/07/22/uk-newscorp-lewis-idUKTRE76L30S20110722|title=Exclusive \u2013 News Corp exec suspected of \"orchestrating\" leak|accessdate=22 July 2011|agency=Reuters|date=22 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jul/22/willlewis-telegraphmediagroup|title=News Corp boss 'linked' to leak of Vince Cable's Rupert Murdoch comments|accessdate=22 July 2011|work=The Guardian|date=22 July 2011|location=London|first=Josh|last=Halliday}}</ref> He broadcast them, to the consternation of ''The Telegraph'' and of Cable who was forced to step aside from his oversight of the BSkyB bid.\n\nDespite the fact that the subject of the transcript was clearly in the public interest, ''Telegraph'' management hired the detective agency Kroll to find the source of the leak.<ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/23/world/europe/23telegraph.html|title = Editor in Battle Over Story Complicate Hacking Scandal\n|last=Van Natta|first=Don|date=July 22, 2011|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianKrollCableAllegation\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/mar/01/daily-telegraph-vince-cable-leak|title = Daily Telegraph internal inquiry clears journalists of Vince Cable leak\n|last=Greenslade|first=Roy|date=March 1, 2011|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, [[Reuters]] reported that the corporate investigations firm [[Kroll Inc.|Kroll]] had \"strong reasons\" to suspect that Lewis had been involved in the leak to Peston. The leaks took place three months after Lewis left the ''Telegraph''. They were seen to be of commercial benefit to News Corporation, the parent company of News International, in relation to the [[News Corporation takeover bid for BSkyB]]. Kroll interviewed several ''Telegraph'' journalists, and examined their email and phone records, but was unable to determine which disgruntled journalists decided to blow the whistle on the ''Telegraph''{{'}}s decision not to publish the Cable comments on Murdoch.\n\nReuters also reported that Kroll had identified that TMG's information security systems were porous and too many people had access to the relevant systems for the leaker to be pinpointed.<ref name= \"ReutersCableAllegation\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-newscorp-lewis/exclusive-news-corp-exec-suspected-in-leak-idUKTRE76L30S20110722|title = Exclusive - News Corp exec suspected in leak\n|last=Hosenball|first=Mark|date=July 22, 2011|website=reuters.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Kroll advised ''The Telegraph'' that because of the number of people who had access to databanks (which included employees for telecoms giant [[BT Group|BT]]) a continued investigation would be unlikely to produce a conclusive result. Kroll did not interview Lewis in the course of the investigation.  \nKroll's own admission the evidence they had gathered was circumstantial and pointed to 15 separate people at ''The Telegraph'' had access to the Cable audio file.<ref name= \"ReutersCableAllegation\"/><ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\"/>\n\nDespite the inconclusive nature of the investigation, ''Telegraph'' editors flew out to America to brief ''The New York Times'', a commercial rival of News Corp.<ref name= \"NYTnewscorpRivalry\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/26/wall-street-journal-new-york-times-rivalry|title = Wall Street Journal goes head-to-head with New York Times\n|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|date=April 26, 2010|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> On 22 July, a piece ran in ''The New York Times'' titled: \"Suspicions About Former Editor in Battle Over Story Complicate hacking Scandal\". The piece, carried the allegation, without evidence, that Lewis was behind the leak.<ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\"/>\n\nLewis responded to ''The New York Times'': \"This is a clear attempt to undermine the strong working relationship between News Corp.'s Management and Standards Committee and the Metropolitan Police Service. Nothing will prevent us from continuing to cooperate fully with Operation Weeting.\"<ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\"/>\n\n==Dow Jones & ''The Wall Street Journal''==\n\nLewis was appointed interim CEO of Dow Jones and Company on 21 January 2014.<ref name= \"GuardianInterim\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/jan/21/will-lewis-appointed-interim-ceo-of-dow-jones|title =Will Lewis replaces ousted Lex Fenwick as CEO of struggling Dow Jones\n|last=Rushe|first=Dominic|date=January 22, 2014|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2014 Lewis was confirmed as CEO of Dow Jones and Company, and publisher of ''The Wall Street Journal'', following the departure of previous CEO Lex Fenwick in 2014.<ref name= \"GuardianDowJonesConfirmed\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/may/09/news-international-executive-dow-jones-will-lewis-phone-hacking|title =Ex-News International executive made permanent head of Dow Jones|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=May 9, 2014|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis had responsibility for the publication of [[the Wall Street Journal]], America's largest newspaper by paid circulation; [[Factiva]], the business information and research tool; [[Barron's (newspaper)|Barron's]], the weekly magazine and ''[[Financial News|Dow Jones Financial News]]'' and Newswires. He has focused on modernising the ''Wall Street Journal'' newsroom, and developing the technology and data businesses.<ref name= \"FTWSJmodernisation\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e9e7e444-aaef-11e6-9cb3-bb8207902122|title =Wall Street Journal slims down amid slide in advertising|last=Garrahan|first=Matthew|date=May 9, 2014|website=ft.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014 the company has experienced growth in readership and revenues, most recently Dow Jones reported 6% growth in 2019 News Corp results.<ref name= \"WSJDowJonesLoss\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/news-corp-swings-to-loss-on-coupon-business-charge-currency-headwinds-11573172452|title =News Corp Swings to Loss on Coupon-Business Charge, Currency Headwinds|last=Alpert|first=Lukas .I|date=May 9, 2014|website=wsj.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Dow Jones Risk & Compliance data business reported 22% revenue growth in the third quarter of fiscal 2019. During his tenure, the WSJ won a [[Pulitzer Prize]]<ref name= \"PoynterWSJPulitzer\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2019/puzzling-over-pulitzers-at-the-wall-street-journal/|title =Puzzling over Pulitzers at The Wall Street Journal|last=HArris Jr.|first=Roy J.|date=April 9, 2019|website=poynter.org|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> for uncovering [[Donald Trump|President Trump's]] relationship with [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]] and payoffs to the adult movie actress, [[Stormy Daniels]]. \n\nIn an interview with ''The New York Times'' he commented on his leadership approach: \"I think that the chief executive or leader should often be the agitator in chief as well... You constantly think about the next iteration of the model and structure.\"<ref name= \"NYTAgitatorinchief\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/04/business/international/dow-jones-wall-street-journal-william-lewis.html|title =The 'Agitator in Chief' of Dow Jones|last=Kolesnikov-Jessop|first=Sonia|date=July 3, 2016|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the company announced a partnership with the UK's [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] to support international engagement for the Theatre company.<ref name= \"WSJandNT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/06/22/1027649/0/en/Wall-Street-Journal-and-National-Theatre-Announce-Global-Storytelling-Partnership.html|title =Wall Street Journal and National Theatre Announce Global Storytelling Partnership|last=Jones|first=Dow|date=June 22, 2017|website=globenewswire.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism of Google and Facebook===\nLewis has regularly made the case for professional media and has criticised technology companies for contributing to the rise of fake news.\n\nIn a panel at [[Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity|the Cannes Lions]] in 2015 he said that: \"the issue for us, and I think the broader industry, is do we run headless chicken-like towards offers from companies like Apple and Facebook to put our content in their walled gardens?. Or do we pause and think together about what the most appropriate way of dealing with these opportunities are and make sure that we don't repeat the mistakes of the past? Professionally created news is of incredible importance in society and has deep moral purpose\".<ref name= \"CannesWalledGardens\">{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/06/25/dow-jones-walled-gardens/|title =Dow Jones chief warns media orgs about getting cozy with Facebook and Apple|last=Ingram|first=Mathew|date=June 25, 2015|website=fortune.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016  interview with Ian Burrell of ''The Drum'' magazine, Lewis accused Facebook and Google of \"killing news\" commenting that he spent years \"badgering away\" at Google and Facebook, trying to persuade them to change their news distribution methods. \"We kept warning them, saying 'This is an accident waiting to happen \u2013 you are treating fake news in the same way as you are treating Wall Street Journal news. This is going to end up biting you.' And so here it is, biting them!<ref name= \"facebookgooglekillingnews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2016/12/01/dow-jones-chief-accuses-google-and-facebook-killing-news|title =Dow Jones chief accuses Google and Facebook of 'killing news'|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=December 1, 2016|website=thedrum.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the ''Evening Standard'' in 2017 he commented: \"Everyone can now see very clearly the grave problem with [[fake news]]. Google has played an incredibly destructive role. And when professional media disappears, bad things follow\".<ref name= \"ESlordofwallstreet\"/>\n\nLewis has since led negotiations with Apple<ref name= \"NYTnewpaidapplenewsWSJ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/20/technology/apple-news-wall-street-journal.html|title =New Paid Apple News Service Said to Feature Wall Street Journal|last=Isaac|first=Mike|date=March 20, 2019|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> and Facebook.<ref name= \"WSJfacebookdeal\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-reaches-deal-with-wall-street-journal-publisher-others-for-news-section-11571431387|title =Facebook Reaches Deal With Wall Street Journal Publisher, Others for News Section|last=Alpert|first=Luka I.|date=October 18, 2019|website=wsj.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> In a newsroom meeting about the WSJ deal with Apple News plus Lewis said that the deal \"will enable us to get our journalism in front of millions of people who may never have paid for our journalism before.\"<ref name= \"WSJAppledealWSJ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-journals-partnership-with-apple-marks-shift-in-strategy-11553556819|title =Wall Street Journal's Partnership With Apple Marks Shift in Strategy|last=Alpert|first=Luka I.|date=October 18, 2019|website=wsj.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, News Corp signed a deal with Facebook who agreed to pay a licensing fee to carry WSJ news on its platform.\n\n=== Support for diversity ===\n\nAs part of a 2016 review into its hiring and compensation practices, Dow Jones retained an outside consultancy, [[Willis Towers Watson]].<ref name= \"PoliticoDowJonesGenderPayHire\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/media/story/2016/04/dow-jones-hires-consultants-to-review-pay-disparity-claims-004489|title =Dow Jones hires consultants to review pay disparity claims|last=Sutton|first=Kelsey|date=April 21, 2016|website=politico.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis vowed to address all pay disparities within the company.<ref name= \"TheCutGernderPay\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2016/03/wsj-dow-jones-vow-close-their-pay-gap.html|title =Dow Jones, The Wall Street Journal Aim to Close Pay Gap|last=Weaver|first=Hilary|date=March 24, 2016|website=thecut.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> In an email to employees he wrote: \"Any pay disparity relating to an employee's race or gender is troubling and inconsistent with the standards I strive to maintain at Dow Jones. We must, as a matter of urgency, address these issues head on.\"<ref name= \"TheHillGenderPay\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/326156-wall-street-journal-staff-rip-white-male-newsroom-control|title =Wall Street Journal staff criticize lack of diversity in newsroom|last=Hensch|first=Mark|date=March 28, 2017|website=thecut.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nIn a lecture to [[Cass Business School]] Lewis said: \"Perhaps the most important role of being a good CEO is making sure you have the right people \u2013 with the most diverse backgrounds \u2013 in the most important jobs inside the company. I can tell you from personal experience that the more diverse a culture, the better the ideas and the increased likelihood of success.\"<ref name= \"CassGenderPay\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.ac.uk/news/2018/april/diversity-key-to-successful-leadership-says-dow-jones-ceo|title =Diversity key to successful leadership, says Dow Jones CEO|last=Ripley|first=Amy|date=March 28, 2017|website=city.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n\n* Journalist of the Year at the UK Press Awards, 2010\n* Honorary Degree of Doctor of Laws from [[Bristol University]] July 2010<ref>http://www.bristol.ac.uk/graduation/honorary-degrees/hondeg10/lewis.html</ref>\n* Honorary Degree of Doctor of Letters from the [[University of Lincoln]] September 2010<ref>https://www.lincoln.ac.uk/home/alumnicommunity/honorarygraduates/</ref> \n* Honorary Degree of Doctor of Science from Cass Business School, 2019.<ref>https://www.city.ac.uk/news/2019/july/william-lewis-honorary-doctorate-summer-graduation</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Sarah Sands]]\n| title = Deputy Editor of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''<small><br/>with Neil Darbyshire</small>\n| years = 2005\u20132006\n| after = [[Ian MacGregor (journalist)|Ian MacGregor]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[John Bryant (journalist)|John Bryant]]\n| title = Editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| years = 2006\u20132009\n| after = [[Tony Gallagher]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2011 News Corporation scandal}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, William}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Financial Times people]]\n[[Category:The Sunday Times people]]\n[[Category:Daily Telegraph journalists]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:News Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|William Lewis}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = William Lewis\n| image         = \n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1969|04|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| education     = [[Whitefield School]]\n| alma_mater    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of Bristol]]\n* [[Department of Journalism, City University]]\n}}\n| occupation    = CEO of [[Dow Jones and Company]]\n| boards        = [[Associated Press]]<ref>https://www.ap.org/about/our-people/leadership-team\n</ref>\n| years_active  = \n| employer      = [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]]\n| known_for     = Publishing the story which led to the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]]; Role as executive member of News Corp's Management and Standards Committee following the [[News International phone hacking scandal]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage| Rebecca Slater |1995}}\n| notable_works = \n| children      = 4\n| relatives     = [[Simon Lewis (public relations officer)|Simon Lewis]] (brother)\n}}\n'''William Lewis''' (born 2 April 1969)<ref name=\"Observer2009\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/24/will-lewis-daily-telegraph-profile|title =Will Lewis: the man with an expense account\n|last=Anthony|first=Andrew|date=May 24, 2009|website=Guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> is a British media executive, chief executive of [[Dow Jones and Company]] and publisher of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''. Earlier in his career he was known as a journalist and then editor.\n\nWhile Editor of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name= \"GuardianMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/may/18/mps-expenses-how-scoop-came-light |title = MPs' expenses: how scoop came to light \u2013 and why journalists fear a 'knock on the door'|last=Brook|first=Stephen|date=May 18, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis led the team that broke the story of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|MPs' expenses scandal]],  which led to the resignation of the [[Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[Michael Martin, Baron Martin of Springburn|Michael Martin]], a further six government ministers and the creation of [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]].<ref>http://www.theipsa.org.uk</ref>\n\nFrom September 2010<ref name= \"MarketingweekNI\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/news-international-hires-will-lewis-to-fill-new-role/ |title = News International hires Will Lewis to fill new role\n|last=Fernandez|first=Joe|date=July 8, 2010|website=Marketingweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> to July 2011, Lewis worked as General Manager of the newspaper publisher [[News International]], playing a role in the company's response to the phone hacking crisis.  In July 2011, following the closure of the ''[[News of the World]]'', Lewis left News International to join the Management and Standards Committee, an independent division led by [[Anthony Grabiner, Baron Grabiner|Lord Grabiner QC]], created by the News Corp board to orchestrate cooperation with multiple law enforcement investigations into News International.\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nWilliam Lewis was born and raised in Hampstead Garden Suburb, North London, England. His father David Lewis M.B.E,<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/news/queens-birthday-honours-2010</ref> worked as a Managing Director of a packaging company and his mother Sally was a teacher. Lewis's primary education was at Brookland Junior school in Hampstead Garden Suburb. His secondary education was at Whitefield school, a comprehensive school in the London Borough of Barnet. After achieving his A levels, Lewis studied for a BSc in Politics and Economics at [[University of Bristol|Bristol University]], where he wrote for the student newspaper, ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]'',<ref name=\"Observer2009\"/> and captained the University 1st football team. Following university Lewis completed a postgraduate diploma in Periodical Journalism at [[City University London|City University]].\n\nIn 1991, Lewis was hired as a finance reporter by ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''.<ref name= \"LevesonLewis\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.discoverleveson.com/witness/Will_Lewis/3960/?bc=1#witnessevidence|title =Witness Statement of William Lewis\n|last=Lewis|first=William|date=January 10, 2012|website=Discoverleveson.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> In 1994 he left the tabloid to take a job in the ''[[Financial Times]]''{{'}} investigative unit. He later became fund management correspondent and then mergers and acquisitions correspondent.<ref name= \"LevesonLewis\"/> In 1999, while posted at the New York office he broke the story of the [[ExxonMobil]] merger,<ref name= \"DowJonesBio\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.dowjones.com/team/william-lewis-3/\n|title =Official biography\n|website=DowJones.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> the biggest industrial merger in US corporate history. The scoop surprised the US business media and helped establish the ''Financial Times'' in the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archives.cjr.org/cover_story/a_narrowed_gaze.php|title=A Narrowed Gaze|last=Starkman|first=Dean|date=January 2012|website=Columbia Journalism Review|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Following this Lewis was promoted to Global News Editor.<ref name=\"Marketing Week2006\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/daily-telegraph-appoints-william-lewis-editor/\n|title =Daily Telegraph appoints William Lewis editor\n|last=Week|first=Marketing|date=Oct 9, 2006|website=marketingweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> He was then poached to become Business Editor at ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', where he remained for three years, from 2002 to 2005.\n\n==Telegraph Media Group==\n\nLewis joined the [[Telegraph Media Group]] as city editor in August 2005 and was made deputy editor of ''The Telegraph'' while he was still working out his notice from ''The Sunday Times''. In October 2006 he became ''The Daily Telegraph''{{'s}} youngest ever editor.<ref name= \"Independent2006\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/will-lewis-the-daily-telegraphs-youngest-ever-editor-426919.html\n|title =Will Lewis: TheDaily Telegraph's youngest ever editor\n|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=Dec 4, 2006|website=Independent.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nOn joining ''The Telegraph'', Lewis described the newspaper as a \"shambles\", with \"no innovation, no culture of improvement, no understanding of the need to perform, of needing to work with your colleagues rather than be at war with them.\"<ref name= \"MediaGuardian100\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jul/11/will-lewis-mediaguardian-100-2009\n|title =The MPs' expenses triumph makes Will Lewis of the Telegraph the highest-rising newspaper editor in the MediaGuardian 100\n|date=July 13, 2009|website=Guardian.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs editor he took control of the newspaper during period of tumultuous change thanks to the decline in print sales and display advertising revenue.<ref name= \"GuardianSweney2009\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jul/13/telegraph-media-group-2008-results|title = Telegraph Media Group reports \u00a315.7m pre-tax loss for 2008|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=July 13, 2009|website=Guardian.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nLewis designed the layout of ''The Telegraph''{{'s}} new Victoria newsroom<ref name= \"MarketingWeekNov2006\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/right-message-wrong-reader/|title = Right Message, Wrong Reader|last=Week|first=Marketing|date=Nov 2, 2006|website=MarketingWeek.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> and saw through the modernisation program which involved senior staff cuts. The move was initially felt to be in conflict with the newspaper's brand and aging readership.<ref name= \"MarketingWeekNov2006\"/>\n\nIn 2007 he was made editor-in-chief of TMG.<ref name= \"DowJonesBio\"/>\n\nDuring his time as editor, he also attempted a broader debate at ''The Telegraph'' about the environment. While the newspapers and website continued to house [[global warming deniers]] such as [[Christopher Booker]] and [[James Delingpole]],<ref>James Randerson [https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2009/feb/25/climate-change-denial-christopher-booker \"Christopher Booker's wilful climate change ignorance gathers pace\"], ''The Guardian'', 25 February 2009</ref> he also recruited Geoffrey Lean, the environmental commentator to write a weekly column and lead the ''Telegraph'''s global warming coverage.<ref>Mark Sweney [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/08/geoffrrey-lean-independent-sunday \"Environment editor Geoffrey Lean to leave Independent on Sunday\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 June 2009</ref>\n\n==Role in the Parliamentary Expenses Scandal==\n\nLewis's involvement in the scandal began when he was told by colleagues that they had been approached by an intermediary on behalf of a source who said that they had four years' worth of MPs' data copied onto a disk. After establishing that the paper would not be breaking the law by accepting the disc, and that the story was in the public interest, Lewis approved negotiation with the intermediary.<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\">{{Cite web|url=https://leveson.sayit.mysociety.org/hearing-10-january-2012/mr-william-lewis|title =Leveson Inquiry, Hearing of Mr William Lewis\n|last=Lewis|first=William|date=January 10, 2012|website=leveson.sayit.mysociety.org|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Lewis told [[the Leveson Inquiry]]: \"the reason [the source] had come to the Telegraph was he wanted to ensure fair and balanced coverage. He wanted to be certain that the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MPs and the Conservative MPs all had their chance to have their day in the sun, as it were.\"<ref name= \"Journalism.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.journalism.co.uk/news/telegraph-paid-middleman--150-000-for-expenses-data/s2/a547418/|title = Telegraph paid middleman \u00a3150,000 for expenses data\n|last=Gunter|first=Joel|date=January 10, 2012|website=Journalism.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> The intermediary, a former [[Special Air Service|SAS]] officer John Wick,<ref name= \"GuardianMPsExpenses\"/> had already offered the story to a number of other newspapers, all of whom had been reluctant to take the risk of publishing, or meet the price set by Wick.<ref name= \"GuardianMPsExpenses\"/>\n\nOnce Lewis's team concluded negotiations with the source,  the Telegraph team had only ten days to investigate the data on the disk which meant wading through more than a million documents.<ref name= \"KirkupMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5563129/MPs-expenses-Out-today-the-censored-version-of-every-MPs-expense-claims.html|title = MPs' expenses: censored version MPs' expenses claims goes online|last=Kirkup|first=James|date=May 18, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Once Lewis saw the information on the disc he realised that he had to run the story. Lewis told [[Brian Leveson|Lord Leveson]]:  \"I became very aware that it was my responsibility to bring this to the public domain. It was no longer going to be a choice for me as editor.\"<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\"/><ref name= \"BBCMPsExpenses\" >{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16494872|title = Leveson Inquiry: Telegraph expenses scoop explained|last=News|first=BBC|date= Jan 10, 2012|website=bbc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLewis stressed to his colleagues that he wanted the Telegraph to be seen as be fair and balanced in their approach. They concluded that they should start with the government and then move into the opposition as it was then, [[the Conservative Party (UK)|the Conservative Party]].<ref name= \"Journalism.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe next stage involved the team writing to each MP to put them on notice that a story was being written, and then to wait for the replies. The first MP to revert to the Telegraph team was [[Secretary of State for Justice]] [[Jack Straw]].<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\"/> Straw replied, confirming the information in the letter and explaining his expenses. Lewis told the Leveson enquiry: \"Only then did I feel able to give the green light to publication that evening.\" He added, \"I remain hugely proud of -- given the intensity with which the MPs' expenses team had to work, the incredible pressure they worked under, continual threat of trying to be stopped what they were doing, I think this record is one we should be proud of.\"<ref name= \"LevesonLewisTestimony\"/> He added: \"I was also aware that this story was laced with risk all round, as the best and most important journalism tends to be.''<ref name= \"BBCMPsExpenses\"/>\n\n===Aftermath of Parliamentary Expenses Scandal===\n\nThe publication of the story led to the resignation of the Speaker of the House of Commons, [[Michael Martin, Baron Martin of Springburn|Michael Martin]], a further six government ministers and the creation of the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority.<ref name= \"BBCAftermathMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48187096|title = MPs' expenses: The Legacy of a Scandal|last=Flinders|first=Professor Matthew|date=May 7, 2019|website=bbc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  A police investigation into the leak was called off in May 2009. A statement issued by Scotland Yard said that although the unauthorised disclosure of information appeared to \"breach public duty\", much of the information was in the process of being prepared for release under the Freedom of Information Act.<ref name= \"PoliceInvestigationMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/may/19/expenses-leak-police|title = MPs' expenses: police will not investigate leaks to media|last=Mulholland|first=Helene|date=May 19, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lewis spoke publicly for the first time about the scandal in a [[BBC Radio 4]] Interview with the BBC Political Editor [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]].<ref name= \"NickRobinsonGuardianMPsExpenses\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jun/30/will-lewis-daily-telegraph-mps-expenses|title = Telegraph's Will Lewis: MPs lost moral authority long before expenses scandal|last=Luft|first=Oliver|date=June 30, 2009|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  In the interview Lewis responded to claims by that his newspaper's coverage had irreparably damaged parliament and democracy as  \"Absolute, complete rubbish.\" In the interview Lewis claimed: \"It is going to open up parliament to a whole new generation of people who understand what it means to be a representative of British citizens,\" he said. He described the removal of criminal MPs from Parliament as \"undeniably a good thing for the United Kingdom.\"\n\nIn a 2017 in an interview with the ''[[Evening Standard]]'',<ref name= \"ESlordofwallstreet\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/business/will-lewis-the-brit-lord-of-wall-street-on-his-battle-with-social-media-giants-and-fake-news-a3625046.html|title = TWill Lewis: The Brit lord of Wall Street on his battle with social media giants and fake news|last=Gwyther|first=Matthew|date=September 1, 2017|website=standard.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis said: \"I think MPs' expenses began that disgust with the political class. Brexit has to be seen within that context. If the House of Lords is our main defence against stupidity, that doesn't make me very happy.\"\n\nIn 2019, Lewis appeared on [[BBC]] documentary marking the 10th anniversary of the scandal.<ref name= \"BBCLewisQueen\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-47669586|title = MPs' expenses editor 'more resolute' after Queen talk|last=News|first=BBC|date=March 25, 2019|website=standard.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis talked about establishment hostility towards the Telegraph newsroom and mentioned a brief meeting with [[Elizabeth II|HM Queen]] wherein she indicated her support and sympathy for the story. Lewis has never disclosed the details of the conversation.\n\nIn a 2019 ''[[New Statesmen]]'' article<ref name= \"NewStatesman\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/05/mps-expenses-very-british-scandal|title = MPs' expenses: a very British scandal|last=Lewis|first=William|date=May 1, 2019|website=standard.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis wrote that the scandal was a missed opportunity:  \"The chance to make radical reforms to our political institutions and how they operate was, however, glaringly (and deliberately) overlooked\u2026. Perhaps the fallout from [[Brexit]] will trigger the root-and-branch reform we need before these challenges can ever hope to be met with the sort of honesty, energy and imagination they demand. Optimistic, perhaps, but real change could be achieved if politicians from across the spectrum \u2013 or people from around Britain who have not previously been involved in politics \u2013 begin to share a proper understanding of where the national interest lies and where it will lie in the very near future.\"\n\n==Departure from the Telegraph Group==\n\nIn the summer of 2009, Lewis took a two-month sabbatical from TMG to attend the [[Advanced Management Program]] at [[Harvard Business School]] \u2013 a compressed version of the college's famed Masters in Business Administration. Towards the end of this period Lewis was joined by TMG chief executive [[Murdoch MacLennan]] who stayed to hammer out Lewis's future at TMG.<ref name= \"ESlordofwallstreet\"/><ref name= \"GuardianHarvard\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2010/jul/09/will-lewis-harvard-business-school|title = Will Lewis and the Harvard Business School big guns|last=Monkey|first=Media|date=July 9, 2010|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Lewis returned to the UK, and founded Euston Partners, a digital development division based in Euston, London, staffed by a team of Telegraph employees.<ref name= \"CampaignNov2009\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/lewis-head-digital-telegraph-group/969846|title = Lewis to head digital for Telegraph group|last=Bowser|first=Jackie|date=November 26, 2009|website=campaign.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  The aim of the division was to find a way for newspapers to make money from the emerging App economy.<ref name= \"PressGazetteEuston\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/euston-partners-dispute-may-have-prompted-lewis-exit/|title = Euston Partners dispute may have prompted Lewis exit|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date= May 6, 2010|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  In January 2010 Lewis took the title of Managing Director Digital, while retaining his position of group editor in chief.  Shortly after this he gave up the daily running of ''Sunday'' and ''Daily Telegraph''. He was succeeded in the editor's chair by [[Tony Gallagher]] in late 2009, but remained editor-in-chief.<ref name= \"PressGazetteMDDigital\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/new-telegraph-editor-as-will-lewis-becomes-md-digital/|title = New Telegraph editor as Will Lewis becomes MD digital|last=Ponsford|first=Dominic|date= Nov 26, 2009|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2010 British Press Awards, ''The Telegraph'' was named the \"National Newspaper of the Year\" for its coverage of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|MPs' expenses scandal]] (named \"Scoop of the Year\"), with Lewis winning \"Journalist of the Year\" for his role.<ref name= \"PressGazetteAward\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/british-press-awards-2010-full-list-of-winners/|title = British Press Awards 2010: Full list of winners|last=Gazette|first=Press|date= Nov 26, 2009|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=March 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccepting his award Lewis said: \"If there was ever a story that proved that news still sells newspapers I suspect this was it.\"<ref name= \"GuardianPressAwards\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/mar/24/british-press-awards-2010-telegraph-expenses|title = Daily Telegraph dominates British Press Awards with expenses expos\u00e9|last=Brook|first=Stephen|date=March 24, 2010|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite this success, all was not well within TMG. Lewis wanted to create a standalone business with a \"start-up mentality\" from the digital unit, whereas MacLennan wanted the Euston-based project to remain within his control at TMG.<ref name= \"MarketingWeekQuits\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.marketingweek.com/will-lewis-quits-telegraph-media-group/|title = Will Lewis Quits Telegraph Media Group|last=McEleny|first=Charlottle|date= May 6, 2010|website=marketingweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2010}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianTelegraphExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/10/will-lewis-telegraph-digital-strategy|title = Will Lewis's exit puts big question over Telegraph's digital strategy|last=Martinson|first=Jane|date=May 10, 2010|website=theguardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  Unable to come to an agreement with MacLennan, Lewis departed on May 5, 2010,<ref name= \"FTTelegraphExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.ft.com/content/6b7a97ac-588d-11df-9921-00144feab49a|title = Lewis departs from Telegraph Group|last=Fenton|first=Ben|date=May 5, 2010|website=ft.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> just six months. The split was described in the press as \"amicable\" but that Maclennan had been \"impatient to see results\". TMG said they would continue to maintain the digital division.<ref name= \"PressGazetteLewisExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/abrupt-exit-for-will-lewis-after-five-years-at-telegraph/|title = Abrupt exit for Will Lewis after five years at Telegraph|last=Gazette|first=Press|date= May 6, 2010|website=pressgazette.co.uk|language=en|access-date=March 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==News International==\n\nIn September 2010 Lewis was hired by News International as group general manager. A key part of this new role was to modernise the company and create streamlined digital newsrooms as he had done at TMG.<ref name= \"GuardianRhids\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/24/will-lewis-telegraph-news-international |title = Will Lewis hires his old Telegraph lieutenants for News International roles\n|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=July 8, 2010|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianMSCExit\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/20/phone-hacking-will-lewis-news-corp |title = Will Lewis likely to leave as News Corp rejigs phone-hacking clean-up team\n|last=Sabbagh|first=Dan|date=July 20, 2012|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlmost immediately on joining, an article in ''[[The New York Times]]'' caused the ongoing issue of illegal phone message interception by the ''News of the World'' to flare up.<ref name= \"NYTphonehacking\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/05/magazine/05hacking-t.html |title = Tabloid Hack Attack on Royals, and Beyond\n|last=Van Natta Jr|first=Don|date=September 1, 2010|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nTowards the end of 2010, Lewis was informed that the company was facing a large number of civil actions relating to phone hacking.<ref name= \"GuardianPCC\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/sep/21/phone-hacking-news-of-the-world|title = PCC to re-examine News of the World phone-hacking evidence\n|last=Robinson|first=James|date=September 21, 2010|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nOn 10 January, Lewis sent out a formal instruction to the IT staff at News International that all evidence relevant to various civil and criminal actions was to be retained on News International's email servers.<ref name= \"HackAttack\">{{cite book |last=Davis |first=Nick |date= |title=Hack Attack: How the truth caught up with Rupert Murdoch |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LVjyAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA324&lpg=PA324&dq=Will+lewis+evidence+preservation+news+international&source=bl&ots=nHz5lK8JB4&sig=ACfU3U10Qakbb2X_fVeqf8IhTjjGC1PkdQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjHoPyR0KnnAhVeTxUIHdQrDiQQ6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Will%20lewis%20evidence%20preservation%20news%20international&f=false |location= |publisher=Random House |page=324 |isbn=9780099572367 |author-link=}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianBrooksMore\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/nov/27/rebekah-brooks-news-international-emails|title = Rebekah Brooks 'ordered deletion of millions of News International emails'\n|last=Davies|first=Nick|date=November 27, 2013|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLewis remained as general manager as the crisis grew. In the aftermath of revelations by ''The Guardian'' that ''News Of the World'' reporters had deleted voicemails of the murdered school girl, [[Murder of Milly Dowler|Milly Dowler]], the ''News of the World'' was closed.<ref name= \"GuardianBrooks\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/mar/03/rebekah-brooks-shutting-news-of-world-protect-bskyb-bid|title = Rebekah Brooks discussed shutting NoW to protect BSkyB bid\n|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=March 3, 2014|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe stepped down as group general manager in July 2011 to take a role as an executive member of the Management and Standards Committee, an independent division of News Corp mandated by the board to cooperate fully with all authorities investigating wrongdoing at News International.<ref name= \"PRWeekMSC\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.prweek.com/article/1080633/news-internationals-will-lewis-simon-greenberg-seconded-newscorp|title = News International's Will Lewis and Simon Greenberg seconded to NewsCorp\n|last=Rogers|first=Danny|date=July 18, 2011|website=prweek.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Management and Standards Committee==\n\nThe formal establishment of the Management and Standards Committee was confirmed on July 18, 2011. The MSC was chaired by [[Anthony Grabiner, Baron Grabiner|Lord Grabiner QC]], a senior commercial lawyer, taking legal advice from the law firm [[Linklaters]]. The MSC reported directly to News Corp board members [[Joel Klein]] and [[Viet D. Dinh|Viet Dinh]].  Both Dinh and Klein were former US Assistant Attorney Generals. Lewis, was named in the press release as a \"full time executive member.<ref name= \"NewsCorpMSCannouce\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://newscorp.com/corporate-governance/uk-newspaper-matters/management-and-standards-committee/|title = Management and Standards Committee\n|last=Corp|first=News|date=2013|website=newscorp.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianNewsCorpMSCannouce\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jul/18/news-corp-hacking-scandal/|title = News Corp appoints independent chairman to deal with hacking scandal|last=Deans|first=Jason|date=July 18, 2011|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Terms of Reference were published on 21 July 2011.<ref name= \"NewsUKMSCterms\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.news.co.uk/2011/07/news-corporations-management-and-standards-committee-msc-has-today-thursday-july-21-published-its-terms-of-reference-tor/|title = News Corporation's Management and Standards Committee (MSC) has today (Thursday, July 21) published its Terms of Reference (ToR)\n|last=Corp|first=News|date=July 21, 2011|website=news.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  \"The MSC was authorised to cooperate fully with all relevant investigations and inquiries in the News of the World phone hacking case, police payments and all other related issues across News International, as well as conducting its own enquiries where appropriate.\"\n\nThe MSC included 100 legal staff from Linklaters, as well as forensic advisers from [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]]. Their role was to review all law enforcement requests for evidence and comply if those requests were relevant to the various ongoing investigations.<ref name= \"ReutersInsideMSC\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-newsinternational/insight-inside-rupert-murdochs-uk-newspaper-clean-up-operation-idUSTRE8110PE20120202|title = Insight: Inside Rupert Murdoch's UK newspaper clean-up operation\n|last=Prodhan|first=Georgina|date=February 2, 2012|website=reuters.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Metropolitan Police Service]] investigations [[Operation Weeting]] (phone hacking) and [[Operation Elveden]] (corruption of public officials) resulted in a string of arrests of News International journalists from October 2011 to Mid 2012, prompting complaints from Sun staff that the paper was subject to a \"witch hunt.\"<ref name= \"NewsCorpCivilWar\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/9080015/News-Corp-descends-into-civil-war-after-latest-Sun-arrests.html|title = News Corp descends into civil war after latest Sun arrests\n|last=Ward|first=Victoria|date=February 13, 2012|website=telegraph.co.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>  Though no Sun journalists were successfully convicted by Operation Elveden, ''News of the World'' feature writer Dan Evans received a 10-month suspended sentence. Operation Weeting successfully convicted ''News of the World'' journalists Neville Thurlbeck and [[Greg Miskiw]] who were both sentenced to six months in prison. Former ''News of the World'' editor [[Andy Coulson]] received an 18-month sentence.<ref name= \"BBCElvedenlegacy\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-35666520|title = Operation Elveden corruption probe ends\n|last=News|first=BBC|date=February 26, 2016|website=bbc.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"BBCWeetingConvictions\">{{Cite web|url= \n https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-28160626|title = Andy Coulson jailed for 18 months over phone hacking\n|last=News|first=BBC|date=July 4, 2014|website=bbc.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 20 July 2012, Lewis began the process of departing the MSC.<ref name= \"GuardianMSCExit\"/>\n\n===Vince Cable leak allegation===\n\nIn December 2010, ''Daily Telegraph'' reporters secretly recorded the UK Business Secretary [[Vince Cable]] making a number of unguarded remarks about the UK government and also his view that \"we have declared war on [[Rupert Murdoch|Murdoch]]\". ''The Telegraph'' reported the remarks about government, but did not publish his views on Murdoch. These views were controversial, because Cable was overseeing in a sub-judicial role the bid by Murdoch's [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] for all of [[BSkyB]]. The remarks about Murdoch were leaked to the BBC's Business Editor, [[Robert Peston]].<ref name=reuters1>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/07/22/uk-newscorp-lewis-idUKTRE76L30S20110722|title=Exclusive \u2013 News Corp exec suspected of \"orchestrating\" leak|accessdate=22 July 2011|agency=Reuters|date=22 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jul/22/willlewis-telegraphmediagroup|title=News Corp boss 'linked' to leak of Vince Cable's Rupert Murdoch comments|accessdate=22 July 2011|work=The Guardian|date=22 July 2011|location=London|first=Josh|last=Halliday}}</ref> He broadcast them, to the consternation of ''The Telegraph'' and of Cable who was forced to step aside from his oversight of the BSkyB bid.\n\nDespite the fact that the subject of the transcript was clearly in the public interest, ''Telegraph'' management hired the detective agency Kroll to find the source of the leak.<ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/23/world/europe/23telegraph.html|title = Editor in Battle Over Story Complicate Hacking Scandal\n|last=Van Natta|first=Don|date=July 22, 2011|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name= \"GuardianKrollCableAllegation\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/mar/01/daily-telegraph-vince-cable-leak|title = Daily Telegraph internal inquiry clears journalists of Vince Cable leak\n|last=Greenslade|first=Roy|date=March 1, 2011|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, [[Reuters]] reported that the corporate investigations firm [[Kroll Inc.|Kroll]] had \"strong reasons\" to suspect that Lewis had been involved in the leak to Peston. The leaks took place three months after Lewis left the ''Telegraph''. They were seen to be of commercial benefit to News Corporation, the parent company of News International, in relation to the [[News Corporation takeover bid for BSkyB]]. Kroll interviewed several ''Telegraph'' journalists, and examined their email and phone records, but was unable to determine which disgruntled journalists decided to blow the whistle on the ''Telegraph''{{'}}s decision not to publish the Cable comments on Murdoch.\n\nReuters also reported that Kroll had identified that TMG's information security systems were porous and too many people had access to the relevant systems for the leaker to be pinpointed.<ref name= \"ReutersCableAllegation\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-newscorp-lewis/exclusive-news-corp-exec-suspected-in-leak-idUKTRE76L30S20110722|title = Exclusive - News Corp exec suspected in leak\n|last=Hosenball|first=Mark|date=July 22, 2011|website=reuters.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Kroll advised ''The Telegraph'' that because of the number of people who had access to databanks (which included employees for telecoms giant [[BT Group|BT]]) a continued investigation would be unlikely to produce a conclusive result. Kroll did not interview Lewis in the course of the investigation.  \nKroll's own admission the evidence they had gathered was circumstantial and pointed to 15 separate people at ''The Telegraph'' had access to the Cable audio file.<ref name= \"ReutersCableAllegation\"/><ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\"/>\n\nDespite the inconclusive nature of the investigation, ''Telegraph'' editors flew out to America to brief ''The New York Times'', a commercial rival of News Corp.<ref name= \"NYTnewscorpRivalry\">{{Cite web|url= \nhttps://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/26/wall-street-journal-new-york-times-rivalry|title = Wall Street Journal goes head-to-head with New York Times\n|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|date=April 26, 2010|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> On 22 July, a piece ran in ''The New York Times'' titled: \"Suspicions About Former Editor in Battle Over Story Complicate hacking Scandal\". The piece, carried the allegation, without evidence, that Lewis was behind the leak.<ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\"/>\n\nLewis responded to ''The New York Times'': \"This is a clear attempt to undermine the strong working relationship between News Corp.'s Management and Standards Committee and the Metropolitan Police Service. Nothing will prevent us from continuing to cooperate fully with Operation Weeting.\"<ref name= \"NYTCableAllegation\"/>\n\n==Dow Jones & ''The Wall Street Journal''==\n\nLewis was appointed interim CEO of Dow Jones and Company on 21 January 2014.<ref name= \"GuardianInterim\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/jan/21/will-lewis-appointed-interim-ceo-of-dow-jones|title =Will Lewis replaces ousted Lex Fenwick as CEO of struggling Dow Jones\n|last=Rushe|first=Dominic|date=January 22, 2014|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2014 Lewis was confirmed as CEO of Dow Jones and Company, and publisher of ''The Wall Street Journal'', following the departure of previous CEO Lex Fenwick in 2014.<ref name= \"GuardianDowJonesConfirmed\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/may/09/news-international-executive-dow-jones-will-lewis-phone-hacking|title =Ex-News International executive made permanent head of Dow Jones|last=O'Carroll|first=Lisa|date=May 9, 2014|website=guardian.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis had responsibility for the publication of [[the Wall Street Journal]], America's largest newspaper by paid circulation; [[Factiva]], the business information and research tool; [[Barron's (newspaper)|Barron's]], the weekly magazine and ''[[Financial News|Dow Jones Financial News]]'' and Newswires. He has focused on modernising the ''Wall Street Journal'' newsroom, and developing the technology and data businesses.<ref name= \"FTWSJmodernisation\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e9e7e444-aaef-11e6-9cb3-bb8207902122|title =Wall Street Journal slims down amid slide in advertising|last=Garrahan|first=Matthew|date=May 9, 2014|website=ft.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014 the company has experienced growth in readership and revenues, most recently Dow Jones reported 6% growth in 2019 News Corp results.<ref name= \"WSJDowJonesLoss\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/news-corp-swings-to-loss-on-coupon-business-charge-currency-headwinds-11573172452|title =News Corp Swings to Loss on Coupon-Business Charge, Currency Headwinds|last=Alpert|first=Lukas .I|date=May 9, 2014|website=wsj.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Dow Jones Risk & Compliance data business reported 22% revenue growth in the third quarter of fiscal 2019. During his tenure, the WSJ won a [[Pulitzer Prize]]<ref name= \"PoynterWSJPulitzer\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2019/puzzling-over-pulitzers-at-the-wall-street-journal/|title =Puzzling over Pulitzers at The Wall Street Journal|last=HArris Jr.|first=Roy J.|date=April 9, 2019|website=poynter.org|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> for uncovering [[Donald Trump|President Trump's]] relationship with [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]] and payoffs to the adult movie actress, [[Stormy Daniels]]. \n\nIn an interview with ''The New York Times'' he commented on his leadership approach: \"I think that the chief executive or leader should often be the agitator in chief as well... You constantly think about the next iteration of the model and structure.\"<ref name= \"NYTAgitatorinchief\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/04/business/international/dow-jones-wall-street-journal-william-lewis.html|title =The 'Agitator in Chief' of Dow Jones|last=Kolesnikov-Jessop|first=Sonia|date=July 3, 2016|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the company announced a partnership with the UK's [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] to support international engagement for the Theatre company.<ref name= \"WSJandNT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/06/22/1027649/0/en/Wall-Street-Journal-and-National-Theatre-Announce-Global-Storytelling-Partnership.html|title =Wall Street Journal and National Theatre Announce Global Storytelling Partnership|last=Jones|first=Dow|date=June 22, 2017|website=globenewswire.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism of Google and Facebook===\nLewis has regularly made the case for professional media and has criticised technology companies for contributing to the rise of fake news.\n\nIn a panel at [[Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity|the Cannes Lions]] in 2015 he said that: \"the issue for us, and I think the broader industry, is do we run headless chicken-like towards offers from companies like Apple and Facebook to put our content in their walled gardens?. Or do we pause and think together about what the most appropriate way of dealing with these opportunities are and make sure that we don't repeat the mistakes of the past? Professionally created news is of incredible importance in society and has deep moral purpose\".<ref name= \"CannesWalledGardens\">{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2015/06/25/dow-jones-walled-gardens/|title =Dow Jones chief warns media orgs about getting cozy with Facebook and Apple|last=Ingram|first=Mathew|date=June 25, 2015|website=fortune.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016  interview with Ian Burrell of ''The Drum'' magazine, Lewis accused Facebook and Google of \"killing news\" commenting that he spent years \"badgering away\" at Google and Facebook, trying to persuade them to change their news distribution methods. \"We kept warning them, saying 'This is an accident waiting to happen \u2013 you are treating fake news in the same way as you are treating Wall Street Journal news. This is going to end up biting you.' And so here it is, biting them!<ref name= \"facebookgooglekillingnews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2016/12/01/dow-jones-chief-accuses-google-and-facebook-killing-news|title =Dow Jones chief accuses Google and Facebook of 'killing news'|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=December 1, 2016|website=thedrum.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the ''Evening Standard'' in 2017 he commented: \"Everyone can now see very clearly the grave problem with [[fake news]]. Google has played an incredibly destructive role. And when professional media disappears, bad things follow\".<ref name= \"ESlordofwallstreet\"/>\n\nLewis has since led negotiations with Apple<ref name= \"NYTnewpaidapplenewsWSJ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/20/technology/apple-news-wall-street-journal.html|title =New Paid Apple News Service Said to Feature Wall Street Journal|last=Isaac|first=Mike|date=March 20, 2019|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> and Facebook.<ref name= \"WSJfacebookdeal\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-reaches-deal-with-wall-street-journal-publisher-others-for-news-section-11571431387|title =Facebook Reaches Deal With Wall Street Journal Publisher, Others for News Section|last=Alpert|first=Luka I.|date=October 18, 2019|website=wsj.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> In a newsroom meeting about the WSJ deal with Apple News plus Lewis said that the deal \"will enable us to get our journalism in front of millions of people who may never have paid for our journalism before.\"<ref name= \"WSJAppledealWSJ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-journals-partnership-with-apple-marks-shift-in-strategy-11553556819|title =Wall Street Journal's Partnership With Apple Marks Shift in Strategy|last=Alpert|first=Luka I.|date=October 18, 2019|website=wsj.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, News Corp signed a deal with Facebook who agreed to pay a licensing fee to carry WSJ news on its platform.\n\n=== Support for diversity ===\n\nAs part of a 2016 review into its hiring and compensation practices, Dow Jones retained an outside consultancy, [[Willis Towers Watson]].<ref name= \"PoliticoDowJonesGenderPayHire\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/media/story/2016/04/dow-jones-hires-consultants-to-review-pay-disparity-claims-004489|title =Dow Jones hires consultants to review pay disparity claims|last=Sutton|first=Kelsey|date=April 21, 2016|website=politico.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> Lewis vowed to address all pay disparities within the company.<ref name= \"TheCutGernderPay\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2016/03/wsj-dow-jones-vow-close-their-pay-gap.html|title =Dow Jones, The Wall Street Journal Aim to Close Pay Gap|last=Weaver|first=Hilary|date=March 24, 2016|website=thecut.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref> In an email to employees he wrote: \"Any pay disparity relating to an employee's race or gender is troubling and inconsistent with the standards I strive to maintain at Dow Jones. We must, as a matter of urgency, address these issues head on.\"<ref name= \"TheHillGenderPay\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/326156-wall-street-journal-staff-rip-white-male-newsroom-control|title =Wall Street Journal staff criticize lack of diversity in newsroom|last=Hensch|first=Mark|date=March 28, 2017|website=thecut.com|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\nIn a lecture to [[Cass Business School]] Lewis said: \"Perhaps the most important role of being a good CEO is making sure you have the right people \u2013 with the most diverse backgrounds \u2013 in the most important jobs inside the company. I can tell you from personal experience that the more diverse a culture, the better the ideas and the increased likelihood of success.\"<ref name= \"CassGenderPay\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.ac.uk/news/2018/april/diversity-key-to-successful-leadership-says-dow-jones-ceo|title =Diversity key to successful leadership, says Dow Jones CEO|last=Ripley|first=Amy|date=March 28, 2017|website=city.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n\n* Journalist of the Year at the UK Press Awards, 2010\n* Honorary Degree of Doctor of Laws from [[Bristol University]] July 2010<ref>http://www.bristol.ac.uk/graduation/honorary-degrees/hondeg10/lewis.html</ref>\n* Honorary Degree of Doctor of Letters from the [[University of Lincoln]] September 2010<ref>https://www.lincoln.ac.uk/home/alumnicommunity/honorarygraduates/</ref> \n* Honorary Degree of Doctor of Science from Cass Business School, 2019.<ref>https://www.city.ac.uk/news/2019/july/william-lewis-honorary-doctorate-summer-graduation</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Sarah Sands]]\n| title = Deputy Editor of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''<small><br/>with Neil Darbyshire</small>\n| years = 2005\u20132006\n| after = [[Ian MacGregor (journalist)|Ian MacGregor]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[John Bryant (journalist)|John Bryant]]\n| title = Editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| years = 2006\u20132009\n| after = [[Tony Gallagher]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2011 News Corporation scandal}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, William}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Financial Times people]]\n[[Category:The Sunday Times people]]\n[[Category:Daily Telegraph journalists]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:News Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Silas T Comberbache", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updating", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Lewis_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "Beistegui Hermanos", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Beistegui Hermanos S.A.\n| logo             = \n| caption          = \n| type             = \n| traded_as        = BH\n| genre            = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 1909\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]]\n| location_country = [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]] (Spain)\n| location         = \n| locations        = Vitoria-Gasteiz: 2<br/>[[\u00c1gueda, Portugal]]: 1\n| area_served      = Europe\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = \n| products         = Bicycles\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n[[Image:BicicletaBH.jpg|thumb|BH bike model ''London'', with some added parts]]\n'''Beistegui Hermanos S.A.''' ('''BH''') is a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[bicycle]] manufacturer founded in 1909 to make [[gun]]s. In 1919, after [[World War I]], BH began making [[bicycles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BH|url=http://pivotcycles.com/mediapdf/Bike%20BH.PDF|publisher=Pivotcycles.com|accessdate=2 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222021420/http://pivotcycles.com/mediapdf/Bike%20BH.PDF|archive-date=22 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Prior to the [[Spanish Civil War]], Beistegui Hermanos also produced firearms, specifically copies of the [[Ruby pistol]] (as the 1914 Model) and [[Mauser C96]] (as the MM31 and MM34).\n \nBH is in [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]], capital of the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], Spain. During the 1960s, the main BH factory in Vitoria manufactured not just frames but everything from saddle to spokes and handlebar. Today, BH has two manufacturing and assembly facilities in Vitoria and another one in [[\u00c1gueda, Portugal]]. The facilities include [[CNC]] laser machining which also produces fitness equipment and parts for [[BMW]] and [[Mercedes Benz]].\n\nIn the early 1990s, BH purchased [[Cycles Peugeot|Peugeot]] and founded [[Cycleurope]]. Cycleurope owns [[Bianchi (bicycle manufacturer)|Bianchi]], Peugeot and [[Gitane]]. In 1996, BH sold Cycleurope to concentrate on home markets of Spain and in [[Portugal]]. In 2001, it re-focused on the pan-European market .\n\nBH manufactures 200,000 bicycles a year, 50% of which are exported to European countries other than Spain.\n\nBH sponsored the [[Direct \u00c9nergie (cycling team)|Direct \u00c9nergie Pro Cycling Team]] in the 2016 and 2017 seasons.\n\n==See also== \n:{{Portal|Sports|Transport}}\n* [[List of electric bicycle brands and manufacturers]]\n* [[Beistegui]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|BH (bicicletas)}}\n* [http://www.bhbikes.com/ BH website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024003420/http://www.bhbikes-us.com/ BH USA website]\n* [http://www.truenorthcycling.com/ BH Canadian Distributor website]\n* [http://www.bhbikesasia.com/ BH BIKES ASIA website]\n* [http://www.i-bh.com.tw/ BH Asia website]\n\n\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Cycle manufacturers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Defunct firearms manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Basque companies]]\n\n{{Spain-company-stub}}\n{{cycle-manufacturer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Beistegui Hermanos S.A.\n| logo             = \n| caption          = \n| type             = \n| traded_as        = BH\n| genre            = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 1909\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]]\n| location_country = [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]] (Spain)\n| location         = \n| locations        = Vitoria-Gasteiz: 2<br/>[[\u00c1gueda, Portugal]]: 1\n| area_served      = Europe\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = \n| products         = Bicycles\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n[[Image:BicicletaBH.jpg|thumb|BH bike model ''London'', with some added parts]]\n'''Beistegui Hermanos S.A.''' ('''BH''') is a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[bicycle]] manufacturer founded in 1909 to make [[gun]]s. In 1919, after [[World War I]], BH began making [[bicycles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BH|url=http://pivotcycles.com/mediapdf/Bike%20BH.PDF|publisher=Pivotcycles.com|accessdate=2 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222021420/http://pivotcycles.com/mediapdf/Bike%20BH.PDF|archive-date=22 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Prior to the [[Spanish Civil War]], Beistegui Hermanos also produced firearms, specifically copies of the [[Ruby pistol]] (as the 1914 Model) and [[Mauser C96]] (as the MM31 and MM34).\n \nBH is in [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]], capital of the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]], Spain. During the 1960s, the main BH factory in Vitoria manufactured not just frames but everything from saddle to spokes and handlebar. Today, BH has two manufacturing and assembly facilities in Vitoria and another one in [[\u00c1gueda, Portugal]]. The facilities include [[CNC]] laser machining which also produces fitness equipment and parts for [[BMW]] and [[Mercedes Benz]].\n\nIn the early 1990s, BH purchased [[Cycles Peugeot|Peugeot]] and founded [[Cycleurope]]. Cycleurope owns [[Bianchi (bicycle manufacturer)|Bianchi]], Peugeot and [[Gitane]]. In 1996, BH sold Cycleurope to concentrate on home markets of Spain and in [[Portugal]]. In 2001, it re-focused on the pan-European market .\n\nBH manufactures 200,000 bicycles a year, 50% of which are exported to European countries other than Spain.\n\nBH sponsored the [[Direct \u00c9nergie (cycling team)|Direct \u00c9nergie Pro Cycling Team]] in the 2016 and 2017 seasons.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of electric bicycle brands and manufacturers]]\n* [[Beistegui]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|BH (bicicletas)}}\n* [http://www.bhbikes.com/ BH website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024003420/http://www.bhbikes-us.com/ BH USA website]\n* [http://www.truenorthcycling.com/ BH Canadian Distributor website]\n* [http://www.bhbikesasia.com/ BH BIKES ASIA website]\n* [http://www.i-bh.com.tw/ BH Asia website]\n\n\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Cycle manufacturers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Defunct firearms manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Basque companies]]\n\n{{Spain-company-stub}}\n{{cycle-manufacturer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "7&6=thirteen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:==See also==  :{{Portal|Sports|Transport}} *List of electric bicycle brands and manufacturers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beistegui_Hermanos"}
{"title_page": "1970\u201371 Midland Football League", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n|competition= Midland Football League\n|season=1970\u201371\n|winners= [[Grantham F.C.|Grantham]]\n|promoted= [[Ilkeston Town F.C. (1945)|Ilkeston Town]]<br>[[Leamington F.C.|Lockheed Leamington]]\n|relegated=\n|matches= 306\n|total goals= 977\n|prevseason= [[1969\u201370 Midland Football League|1969\u201370]]\n|nextseason= [[1971\u201372 Midland Football League|1971\u201372]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1970\u201371 Midland Football League''' season was the 71st in the history of the [[Midland Football League (1889)|Midland Football League]], a [[association football|football]] competition in [[England]].\n\n==Clubs==\nThe league featured 17 clubs which competed in the previous season, along with one new club:\n*[[Frickley Colliery F.C.|Frickley Colliery]], joined from the [[Cheshire County League]]\n\n===League table===\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|use_goal_ratio=y\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=GRA|name_GRA=[[Grantham F.C.|Grantham]]\n|team2=ARN|name_ARN=[[Arnold F.C.|Arnold]]\n|team3=FRI|name_FRI=[[Frickley Colliery F.C.|Frickley Colliery]]\n|team4=ILK|name_ILK=[[Ilkeston Town F.C. (1945)|Ilkeston Town]]\n|team5=ALF|name_ALF=[[Alfreton Town F.C.|Alfreton Town]]\n|team6=LEA|name_LEA=[[Leamington F.C.|Lockheed Leamington]]\n|team7=WOR|name_WOR=[[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]]\n|team8=SKE|name_SKE=[[Skegness Town F.C.|Skegness Town]]\n|team9=SUT|name_SUT=[[Ashfield United F.C.|Sutton Town]]\n|team10=RET|name_RET=[[Retford Town F.C.|Retford Town]]\n|team11=BEL|name_BEL=[[Belper Town F.C.|Belper Town]]\n|team12=LEU|name_LEU=[[Long Eaton United F.C.|Long Eaton United]]\n|team13=HEA|name_HEA=[[Heanor Town F.C.|Heanor Town]]\n|team14=LOU|name_LOU=[[Loughborough United F.C.|Loughborough United]]\n|team15=ASH|name_ASH=[[Ashby Institute F.C.|Ashby Institute]]\n|team16=BOS|name_BOS=[[Boston Town F.C.|Boston]]\n|team17=STA|name_STA=[[Stamford F.C.|Stamford]]\n|t